Prompt

A player’s role on a team can change due to trades, injuries, or coaching decisions, often leading to a significant increase or decrease in their average ice time. But how does this affect their performance? In this project, you will use game-by-game and season-level player data to explore the relationship between average ice time and various performance metrics for various different types of players. Your goal is to find some general trends, and to offer a sense of what to expect when a player’s ice time changes.

Data-sets and Data Cleaning code used for this project:

“players” data: Consists of random names and values such as corsi, primary assists, defensive plays, etc that do not correlate to LA Kings players. After playing with the data set to try and retrieve quantifiable results, it became obvious that this data set did not contain reliable information.

“playerstats” data: Similar to the player’s data explained above, this data set is difficult to work with because it does not have player names, only player_id making it difficult to measure.

“Kings_All” data: Dataset that initially combined all the data we web scraped from Money-Puck covering the 23-24 and 24-25 seasons (playoffs included). This was the groups first attempt at making a combined data set for visualization creation and regression modeling. This dataset was not really used in our final analysis but it certainly helped us build a foundation.

“Kings2” data: This is the data set that we used for most of our regression models and data visualizations. What was unique about this data set was that Ryan was able to create a few df functions that helped standardize values across columns, apply the janitor package to clean names, and then lastly create a column “play_uid” that accurately tracked LA Kings players across the two different seasons. This data set was extremely helpful in creating and understanding what variables impact ice time.

# calculate performance stats
rename_fields <- function(df) {
  df |> 
    rename(
      player_id = player_id,
      name = name,
      pos = pos,
      games_played = games_played,
      icetime = icetime_minutes,
      goals = goals_7,
      xgoals = expected_goals,
      points60 = points_per_60_minutes,
      xgoals60 = expected_goals_per_60_minutes
    ) |> 
    mutate(
      goals = as.integer(goals),
      assists = as.integer(assists),
      points = as.integer(points),
      xgoals = as.numeric(xgoals),
      points60 = as.numeric(points60),   
      xgoals60 = as.numeric(xgoals60),   
      icetime = as.numeric(icetime),
      goals60 = ifelse(icetime > 0, (goals / icetime) * 60, NA_real_)
    ) |> 
    select(player_id, name, pos, season, context, games_played, icetime,
           goals, assists, points, xgoals, goals60, points60, xgoals60)
}

# apply function to all datasets
Regular_2425_clean <- rename_fields(Regular_2425)

# load, tag, and clean
load_and_prepare <- function(path, season, context) {
  read_csv(path) |>
    mutate(season = season, context = context) |>
    clean_names() |>
    select(
      name, pos, games_played, icetime_minutes, expected_goals, goals_7,
      assists, points, primary_assists, secondary_assist, shifts,
      share_of_possible_icetime, hits, season, context
    )
}

reg_2324   <- load_and_prepare("Kings.Reg.23.24.csv", "2023-24", "Regular")
play_2324  <- load_and_prepare("Kings_Playoffs_23-24.csv", "2023-24", "Playoffs")
reg_2425   <- load_and_prepare("24-25.regular.csv", "2024-25", "Regular")
play_2425  <- load_and_prepare("Kings_Playoffs_24-25-1.csv", "2024-25", "Playoffs")

# numeric variables
standardize_core <- function(df) {
  df |> 
    mutate(
      games_played = as.numeric(games_played),
      icetime = as.numeric(icetime_minutes),
      expected_goals = as.numeric(expected_goals),
      goals = as.numeric(goals_7),
      assists = as.numeric(assists),
      points = as.numeric(points),
      primary_assists = as.numeric(primary_assists),
      secondary_assists = as.numeric(secondary_assist),
      shifts = as.numeric(shifts),
      share_of_possible_icetime = as.numeric(share_of_possible_icetime),
      hits = as.numeric(hits),
      name = str_trim(name)
    ) |>
    select(
      name, pos, games_played, icetime, expected_goals, goals, assists,
      points, primary_assists, secondary_assists, shifts,
      share_of_possible_icetime, hits, season, context
    )
}

# standardization
reg_2324   <- standardize_core(reg_2324)
play_2324  <- standardize_core(play_2324)
reg_2425   <- standardize_core(reg_2425)
play_2425  <- standardize_core(play_2425)

# combine datasets
Kings <- bind_rows(reg_2324, play_2324, reg_2425, play_2425)

# player_uid  per-game metric
Kings2 <- Kings |>
  group_by(name) |>
  mutate(player_uid = cur_group_id()) |>
  ungroup() |>
  mutate(icetime_pg = icetime / games_played)

How Ice Time Shapes NHL Performance

Ice time at its core measures how long a player is on the ice during a game, commonly reported in minutes per game or as total minutes across a season. Although on the surface this stat seems simple, the metric explores deeper insights behind player opportunity, trust, and impact.

Ice time is not distributed evenly across an NHL roaster. Coaches allocate ice time strategically and some variables impacting ice-time may unquantifiable. Star forwards might clock 20+ minutes, while fourth-line players or depth defense men log only a fraction of that (4-5 minutes). This uneven distribution can not only detail a players capabilities, it can also expose driving forces behind how a player produces. More chances on ice provide players more opportunities to shoot, assist, pass, and defend. Thus providing players the chance to contribute towards team success.

Yet, the relationship between ice time and performance isn’t always linear. Some players thrive with increased ice time, while others see their efficiency dip. Injuries, trades, or coaching adjustments can shift a player’s role midseason, altering their average ice time and, potentially, their performance outcomes.

That raises an important question: What variables are most important in determining ice time for LA Kings players over the past two seasons? Which LA Kings players are the most intriguing to explore based off of these critical variables in addition to changes in ice time and our own intuition.

In this blog post, we explore this question using recent data from the NHL (via MoneyPuck, & LA Kings data). By utilizing regular season and playoff data, our team looks to discover which variables are the most important in predicting ice time.

To elaborate on that, we decided to create visualizations and re-run regression models based on the variables we thought would be the most intriguing to explore, along with variables that showed confidence in impacting ice time.

We concluded that, given the nature of sports in general, how hockey is played, and the different roles that players have on a team, we will not be able to come up with a perfect regression. Rather, we concluded that a regression is just a model used to further explore different variables, to change different aspects, and imagine the impact it can have on your team in certain scenarios. It is not an end-all be-all. We supported this argument from a qualitative side, exploring Drew Doughty and Brandt Clarkes previous seasons and showing time on ice can be predicted through different ways of adding value as a player.

After running regressions from the “Kings_All” data set, we pivoted and created the Kings2 data, which really let us explore more about these variables. In the Kings_All data, points, xgoals, and games_played seemed to be the most important in explaining ice time. Our team felt that this data set did not allow us to explore more variables that could also be important, yet it was crucial to run regression on Kings_All to further understand ice time.

To evaluate how ice time affects player performance, we built a series of regression models using game-by-game and season-level NHL data. After refining the model through multicollinearity checks, interaction testing, and variable standardization, we arrived at a final linear model that predicts player point totals based on expected goals, primary assists, and secondary assists. These three variables were all highly significant, with each one-standard-deviation increase associated with a 7-point boost in season scoring. Surprisingly, average ice time per game was not a significant predictor, suggesting that opportunity alone doesn’t drive production, a player’s quality of offensive involvement is much more impactful. This adds to our argument of trying to analyze players from both a qualitative and quantitative perspective about their value added to the team. The model achieved an R-Squared of 97.4% and performed consistently, confirming its strengths.

To understand what drives a player’s average ice time per game, we built a series of regression models using NHL player data. Our team arrived at a final model that predicts icetime_pg using shifts, secondary assists, and expected goals. The number of shifts had a nonlinear effect, making it the strongest predictor of ice time. A one-standard-deviation increase in secondary assists was associated with a +1.1-minute increase, while expected goals had a small but significant negative effect, suggesting that players who generate high shot quality may be efficient scorers in limited time. The model explained 72% of the variance in ice time (via cross-validation) with a root mean squared error of 1.96 minutes, indicating strong performance and practical predictive utility. These findings suggest that ice time is more influenced by a player’s role and supporting contributions than by primary scoring metrics alone.

combined <- full_join(
  select(Regular_2324, name, TOI_23 = icetime_minutes, Points_23 = points),
  select(Regular_2425, name, TOI_24 = icetime_minutes, Points_24 = points),
  join_by(name == name)
) %>%
  mutate(
    Delta_TOI = TOI_24 - TOI_23,
    Delta_Points = Points_24 - Points_23)


top_names <- combined %>%
  slice_max(order_by = Points_24, n = 10) %>%
  pull(name)

combined <- combined %>%
  mutate(name_legend = if_else(name %in% top_names, name, "Other"))

ggplot(combined, aes(x = Delta_TOI, y = Delta_Points)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = name_legend), size = 3) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "black") +
  labs(
    title = "Impact of Change in Ice Time on Player Performance",
    x = "Change in Time on Ice (Minutes)",
    y = "Change in Total Points",
    color = "Player (Top 10 shown)"
  ) +
  theme_bw()

The graph is super helpful to compare LA Kings players across there changes in total points and ice time. Whats super interesting to see is Alex LaFerriere’s exceptional increase in total points (20) with a 500 minute increase in time on ice. This shows that for a player like Laferriere, a change in ice time DID directly affect his performance. With more time on ice he was able to successfully contribute to his teams success.

Although secondary assists may seem like a niche statistic with limited insight, our regression models indicate that they are actually a strong predictor of ice time. That’s why I wanted to examine how this variable played out over the last two seasons. What stands out during the 2023–24 playoffs is the number of players who recorded at least one secondary assist.

Given that the LA Kings have now been eliminated by the Oilers in three consecutive playoff runs, it’s especially interesting to see how assist metrics were affected in a postseason where the team’s playoff hopes were once again cut short by the same opponent.

Looking at individual players, it’s encouraging to see Anze Kopitar rise in the ranks during the 2024–25 playoffs. While primary and secondary assists don’t tell the full story, they offer a meaningful starting point for analyzing how specific contributions on the ice relate to overall ice time and ultimately, player impact.

Kings2 %>%
  group_by(player_uid, name) %>%

  arrange(desc(avg_icetime)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(name, avg_icetime), y = avg_icetime)) +
  geom_col(fill = "black") +
  coord_flip() + 
  labs(
    title = "Average Ice Time per Player (All Seasons & Contexts)",
    x = "Player",
    y = "Average Ice Time (Minutes)"
  ) +
  theme_bw()

In wrapping up this analysis, the Kings_All dataset highlighted points, expected goals (xGoals), and games played as the most important variables influencing player ice time. In contrast, our regression models using the Kings2 dataset pointed to expected goals, primary and secondary assists, and shifts as key predictors. What made this exploration particularly compelling was seeing how these regression results played out on an individual level, offering measurable insights into the roles of players like Drew Doughty, Anze Kopitar, and even emerging contributors like Brandt Clarke. These statistical patterns helped us better understand not just who was on the ice, but why.

To circle back to our main point, we will never find a perfect regression model that will completely predicts ice time. Yet through exploratory analysis and general curiosity, we can now confidently say that expected goals, games played, primary and secondary assists, and shifts show confidence in predicting ice time.
